column1: event,"Last 20 World Series Champions: 13 from the AL and 7 from the NL
That does not seem so dominant, however 2 of the last 3 NL champions were the Marlins, who are to be put kindly a ""special case"".
8 of the 13 times the AL won the championship the NL team in the World Series has a better regular season record.
6 NL Championship series have gone to a game 7 in the past 20 years
4 AL Championship series have gone to a game 7 in the past 20 years (two of those being the first two years in question

In the 90's and 2000's there have been more mediocre NL playoff teams that have battled back and forth but in the end could not contend with the AL champion. Examples: 2005 Boston Red Sox, 1996 New York Yankees
Could the balance of power be shifting?
No, it does not seem to be at the moment. Look at recent Power Rankings based on record.
ESPN.com has the top ten split 5 AL and 5 NL.
But look deeper. Who (at this point) seem to be the real contenders?
Only 2 NL teams are in my top 7.
It is a fact that major AL markets (Boston, New York, Cali) see the NL as the B league while AL is the real major leagues."

event,"

Watching NBA on ABC is painful enough. With the addition of Mark Jackson things have gone from bad to awful. Mark Jackson was a tremendous point guard during his career, gaining most fame from his stint with the Pacers. He is, I believe, second all-time in assists.

Yesterday during the Heat/Lakers game Jackson claimed that when all is said and done Kobe Bryant will be the greatest player ever in the history of the game. I could hear Scottie Pippen and Dan Patrick's respective jaws hitting the floor. The point was brought up, how can you say that taking Michael Jordan into consideration? Mark Jackson said that he never thought he would say it after playing against Michael but Kobe will be better.
column2:
If you are familar with ESPN you know how sarcastic Dan Patrick can be. As they went to commercial, he said he was speachless and told Jackson to take them to break.

Later, still stunned with Jackson's first remarks he made another blunder. He changed his MVP vote that he made only hours prior. He claimed Lebron James was a lock for the award and then flip-flopped to the Kobe fan club once again. When questioned by Patrick he said that he did just change it but at this time Kobe gets his vote. Patrick moved on taking about a different subject only then to go back to the MVP flip-flop saying, ""It's been a few minutes are you still saying Kobe for MVP""?

If ABC's coverage needed
column3: to add to their already hard to watch coverage,&nbsp
column4:
they found the icing on the cake with this one.

"

event,"When you look at the season so far there is no clear favorite. The Mets are off to the start that they should be at least looking at that tema on paper. On the other hand, the White Sox improved on paper but have struggled againt Cleveland and Kansas City of all teams. The Red Sox have handled their easy early schedule relatively well but more importantly Schilling, Becket, Wakefield and Papelbon are all pitching well. The Yankees have been putting up the runs everyone expected while pitching has been questionable. However the Big Unit has pitched well in a few outings, a good sign for them. If the Blue Jays get any time of pitching they can be very dangerous with that offense. If not for a 1-2 series with the Mariners (who might be better than expected) the Indians would be off to a fast start.

event,"Certainly everyone is sad to see Adam Vinatieri's departure. He is a future Hall of Famer and helped bring the Patriots to the prominence they enjoy right now.

I want to say that Adam is not going to be the biggest loss this off-season.

David Givens is a great WR who is on the upswing, while Vinatieri is on his way out. Who is in our receiving corps right now? We've lost Givens and and Timmy Dwight.

We picked up Reche Caldwell from the Chargers. He could be a Dwight type player, but can he return punts? Troy Brown is getting old, he cannot play on both sides of the ball and special teams like he was a few years ago. Deion Branch is going to be looking for a payday when his contract is up, and Bethel Johnson has disappeared off of Belichick's radar for appart disciplinary issues.

So where does this leave up right now?

-Troy Brown, going on 36 years of age
-Reche Caldwell, unproven in any role
-Bethel Johnson, great gifts and un tapped potential

We need to look beyond the draft here. We can't pick up 5 receivers and hope that 2 or 3 of them work out. Getting one more wide out is a must. This is where Joe Jurevicius would have made perfect sense. A WR with SIZE and a great work ethic. Romeo got a steal here.

I'm just very uncertain how people can call this a Super Bowl contending team. Help is needed in many areas beyond the WR spot.
column4: -Running Back, who knows what Dillion is going to do this year
column10: -Linebacker, specifically LOLB to replace Willie McGinest
column13: -Corner Back, where do you start? Hobbs and Samuel have shown flashes but we need a proven guy to lead them
column16: -Safety, where does Harrison fit in? Will Wilson even be a safety next year?
column19:
-Ofensive Line, iIt is a must to keep that line in order

So byebye Adam but I think it hurts more to see Givens go, not to mention McGinest.

""It's going to be hard to see Vinatieri wearing #4 in Indy... in my mind that number will always belong to Jim Harbaugh."""

Keys:
-Hunger
Both teams should be hungry for this playoff win. Both teams were not in the playoffs last year and have been absent for several years. Whoever comes out playing hard could take a big advantage.
-Defense
Both the Bucs and Skins have solid defenses. Whichever team will step up and make a big play or two could have the upper hand.
column2:
-Brunnell vs. Simms
No, not Phil, Chris. Will Brunnell's experience be a factor?

The Redskins are 1-5 when scoring 21 or less. As DECENT as their defense is, they are not or at least have not been a shut down defense. If Portis can get to the 100 yard mark and open up the passing game then the Skins could have a field day on the Bucs defense. Do they need to though? The Bucs offense has been nothing spectacular, so this could be game number two where a touchdown or two is enough to win for the Skins.

column2:
-Pressure Leftwich
He has not seen live action in well over a month, pressure him and do not let him pick apart the tattered secondary.
column3:
-Stop the Run
Both teams must stop the run. The Jags have a solid run game, therefore the Pats must make a point to stop it. On the other hand, the Jaguars need to stop the Pats run game for different reasons. They can not let the Patriots balance their offense. If the Patriots get near 100 yards they can easily take the game. Time of possession could be huge in what should be a close, tough game.

column1: I suppose the fact that the Jags put up 40 an 38 points in the finally two weeks of the season should be a scary thought. On top on that they did not have starting quarterback Byron Leftwich. However those last two games were against the Texans and Titans. The week before the Texans game, the 49ers held the Jags to 10 points.

If you are reading other previews of this game you must have seen that the jags are winners of eight of their last nine and are
playing their best football"". Look at there schedule during this time:

Not just one great team, only one GOOD team, the Colts. Not to mention the Jags lost that one and only competitive game. Playing there best football? Since when is beating the Texans, Titans, Cardinals, Browns and 49ers by a touchdown or less good football?

On the other side of things, the Jaguars defense was ranked 6th overall this past year. No one is talking about them still. They went very under looked throughout the regular season. What wins playoff games? A solid quarterback and a good defense and with Leftwich back, it looks like the pieces COULD be coming together for the Jags.

If they can take one or both of the Charlotte and Dayton games at home, that could be a big win. The same goes for Xavier at the end of the season. All three of these teams seem to be evenly matched with the Minutemen.

"
